problem:cant parse the response of the server in the browser and it shows text/javascript or JSON Parse Error

solution:This error occurs when the server is returning a response with a content type of text/javascript, but the browser is unable to parse it as JavaScript or JSON. This can happen if the server is returning an error page (like a 404 Not Found) instead of the expected JavaScript or JSON response. To fix this issue, you can check the server logs to see if there are any errors being thrown when handling the request. Additionally, you can use browser developer tools to inspect the network requests and responses to identify any issues with the content being returned by the server.




problem:when we acces the log file without making the propogate true we need to set the root as a handler rather than django!,as root is a default logger that is used when no other logger is specified. By setting the root logger as a handler, we can ensure that all log messages are captured and written to the log file, regardless of which logger is being used in the code. This allows us to see all log messages in the log file, including those from the Django framework itself, which can be helpful for debugging and troubleshooting issues with the server.

solution:In the logging configuration, we need to set the root logger as a handler rather than the django logger. This is because the root logger is the default logger that is used when no other logger is specified. By setting the root logger as a handler, we can ensure that all log messages are captured and written to the log file, regardless of which logger is being used in the code. This allows us to see all log messages in the log file, including those from the Django framework itself, which can be helpful for debugging and troubleshooting issues with the server.



